<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-408-186  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 408 186.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  July 3 1989 v6 n26 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Server reduces bottlenecks in database queries. (Advanced DataServers' dedicated database server) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kovsky, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Advanced Data Servers Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Advanced Data Servers SQL Mach 1 (File Server) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionData Base ServersNetwork ManagementQuery ProcessingDedicated ProcessorsInformation Storage and Retrieval.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Server Reduces Bottlenecks in Database QueriesandM;BOISE, Idaho -- A new dedicated database server will be brought to marketnext month by Advanced Data Servers (ADS), potentially reducing networktraffic and increasing the speed for retrieving database information.andM;ADS' marketing manager, Brad Surkamer, said the SQL Mach 1 is the firstproduct to take a hardware approach to solving the bottleneck probleminherent in database queries.andM;According to Surkamer, a typical SQL network database works in such a waythat any specific query--such as how many customers spent more than a certainamount of money in a given period--would require that the complete contentsof the customer database be read into the server's processor.andP;  The CPU wouldsort the data for the correct answer and return the proper field ofinformation to the user.andM;Instead of bogging down the network server with the sorting and transmissionof such large data blocks, the ADS architecture provides a dedicated Intel80286 microprocessor along with a patented relational co-processor to readand sort the data directly from the hard disk in which the database isstored, Surkamer said.andM;&quot;As a result, the information [sent back to the network] from theco-processor is much reduced and closer to the final answer,&quot; Surkamer said.andM;Company officials claim the SQL Mach 1 database machine performs 30 timesfaster than Microsoft's SQLServer.andM;To the host network, the Mach 1 appears as a software-based server, Surkamersaid.andM;The basic configuration of the SQL Mach 1, which will become available todevelopers Aug. 1, includes a 320MB hard disk, 4MB of RAM, a 150MB tape driveand an internal modem.andP;  The system is priced at $23,950 but will be offeredto developers for $11,975, according to the officials.andM;Options include additional disk drives for as much as 1.8GB on a singlesystem and RAM upgrades that add as much as 12MB of on-board memory.andO;Ethernet or direct-connect interface cards will also be available.andM;For more information, Advanced Data Servers, a subsidiary of Extended SystemsInc., can be contacted at P.O. Box 4937, Boise, ID 83711, (208) 322-7800.andO;</TEXT></DOC>